      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Here are the results for the paper by Valle-Pérez, Camargo, and Louis:\n\n## \"Deep Learning Generalizes Because the Parameter-Function Map is Biased Towards Simple Functions\"\n\n**Authors:** Guillermo Valle-Pérez, Chico Q. Camargo, Ard A. Louis\n\n**Venue:** "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "ICLR 2019"
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": " — "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "presented at the Seventh International Conference on Learning Representations, 6–9 May 2019, New Orleans, Louisiana, US."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n**ArXiv:** [1805.08522](https://arxiv.org/abs/1805.08522) | **OpenReview:** [rye4g3AqFm](https://openreview.net/forum?id=rye4g3AqFm)\n\n### Summary\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Deep neural networks (DNNs) generalize remarkably well without explicit regularization even in the strongly over-parametrized regime where classical learning theory would instead predict that they would severely overfit."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": " "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "While many proposals for some kind of implicit regularization have been made to rationalise this success, there is no consensus for the fundamental reason why DNNs do not strongly overfit."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\nThe paper's core argument: "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "By applying a very general probability-complexity bound recently derived from algorithmic information theory (AIT), the authors argue that the parameter-function map of many DNNs should be exponentially biased towards simple functions."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "They provide clear evidence for this strong simplicity bias in a model DNN for Boolean functions, as well as in much larger fully connected and convolutional networks trained on CIFAR10 and MNIST."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "As the target functions in many real problems are expected to be highly structured, this intrinsic simplicity bias helps explain why deep networks generalize well on real world problems."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n### PAC-Bayes Bounds\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "This picture also facilitates a novel PAC-Bayes approach where the prior is taken over the DNN input-output function space, rather than the more conventional prior over parameter space."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": " "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "If we assume that the training algorithm samples parameters close to uniformly within the zero-error region, then the PAC-Bayes theorem can be used to guarantee good expected generalization. By exploiting connections between DNNs and Gaussian processes to estimate the marginal likelihood, they produce relatively tight generalization PAC-Bayes error bounds which correlate well with the true error on realistic datasets such as MNIST and CIFAR10."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n### Keywords\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Generalization, deep learning theory, PAC-Bayes, Gaussian processes, parameter-function map, simplicity bias."
      }
